<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.geocities.com/Athens/Crete/4516/gp/Glasnost-Perestroika.html" class="external text" title="http://www.geocities.com/Athens/Crete/4516/gp/Glasnost-Perestroika.html" rel="nofollow">Glasnost-Perestroika: A Model Potemkin Village by Steve Montgomery</a>, from <a href="http://www.geocities.com/athens/crete/4516/" class="external text" title="http://www.geocities.com/athens/crete/4516/" rel="nofollow">The Perfect Law of Liberty</a><sup class="noprint Inline-Template"><span title="The material in the vicinity of this tag needs to be fact-checked with the cited source(s)&#160;since July 2007" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title="Wikipedia:Verifiability">verification needed</a></i>]</span></sup></li>
<li id="cite_note-5"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/opinion/2009/0217/1224241277965.html" class="external free" title="http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/opinion/2009/0217/1224241277965.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/opinion/2009/0217/1224241277965.html</a> Why is Dublin the Potemkin Village of contemporary capitalism, full of fronts with very little behind them?</li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6" title="">^</a></b> <i>Tohmatsu, Haruo and H.P. Wilmott,</i> A Gathering Darkness: The Coming of War to the Far East and the Pacific, 1921–1942 <i>(Lanham, MD: SR Books, 2004) 38–39.</i></li>
</ol>
</div>
